{"id":34058,"title":"Comparative scanning electron microscopy of bullous diseases.","abstract":"The purpose of this study is to compare scanning electron microscopy findings of the blister roof in three distinct bullous diseases: one intraepidermal acantholytic (pemphigus foliaceus); one due to hemidesmosomal dysfunction (bullous pemphigoid); and one secondary to anchoring fibril dysfunction - type VII collagen (dystrophic epidermolysis bullosa). In pemphigus foliaceus, acantholytic phenomena were readily demonstrated. In bullous pemphigoid, the epidermis had a solid aspect. In dystrophic epidermolysis bullosa a net was seen in the blister roof. ","date":"2014-04-28","categories":"Congenital Hereditary and Neonatal Diseases and Abnormalities","split":"train","url":"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24770520","annotations":[{"name":"Epidermis (skin)","weight":0.824228,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epidermis_(skin)"},{"name":"Collagen","weight":0.809719,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collagen"},{"name":"Electron microscope","weight":0.695533,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electron_microscope"},{"name":"Cutaneous conditions","weight":0.685313,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cutaneous_conditions"},{"name":"Blister","weight":0.513715,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blister"},{"name":"Scanning electron microscope","weight":0.509059,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scanning_electron_microscope"},{"name":"Pemphigus","weight":0.494375,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pemphigus"},{"name":"Bullous pemphigoid","weight":0.43179,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bullous_pemphigoid"},{"name":"Hemidesmosome","weight":0.395833,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hemidesmosome"},{"name":"Epidermolysis bullosa","weight":0.390981,"wikipedia_article":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epidermolysis_bullosa"},{"name":"Pemphigus foliaceu